{
  "What are the three main types of scientific investigations?": "",
  "Controlled experiments, observational studies, and models or simulations": "",
  "Hypotheses, conclusions, and data tables only used in laboratories": "",
  "Qualitative studies, quantitative studies, and theoretical calculations": "",
  "Indoor experiments, outdoor experiments, and computer-based experiments": "",
  "The three main types of scientific investigations are controlled experiments (testing variables), observational studies (watching without manipulating), and models/simulations (representing real systems). Each serves different purposes.": "",
  "In which type of investigation does the scientist deliberately change a variable?": "",
  "An observational study": "",
  "A controlled experiment": "",
  "A descriptive study only": "",
  "A natural observation only": "",
  "In a controlled experiment, the scientist deliberately changes (manipulates) the independent variable while keeping all other variables constant. This allows cause-and-effect relationships to be determined.": "",
  "What type of investigation involves watching and recording data without changing anything?": "",
  "A controlled experiment with a control group": "",
  "An observational study that records natural events": "",
  "A simulation using computer software to model": "",
  "A laboratory experiment with multiple test groups": "",
  "An observational study involves collecting data by watching and recording events as they naturally occur, without manipulating any variables. Astronomers observing stars and ecologists counting animals are examples.": "",
  "Which type of investigation can establish cause-and-effect relationships?": "",
  "Only observational studies done in natural settings": "",
  "Only surveys conducted with large groups of people": "",
  "Controlled experiments with manipulated variables": "",
  "Descriptive studies using only qualitative data noted": "",
  "Only controlled experiments can establish cause-and-effect relationships because they isolate one variable while controlling all others. Observational studies can show correlations but cannot prove causation.": "",
  "A scientist counts the number of bird species in a forest each month for a year. What type of investigation is this?": "",
  "A field observation study": "",
  "A computer simulation run": "",
  "A laboratory experiment": "",
  "This is a field observation because the scientist is collecting data in a natural setting without manipulating any variables. She is simply recording what she observes about bird populations over time.": "",
  "When would a scientist use a model or simulation instead of a real experiment?": "",
  "When the real event is too dangerous, expensive, large, or slow to test directly": "",
  "When the scientist wants to guarantee the exact results they are expecting": "",
  "When the scientist does not want to collect any real data from testing": "",
  "When the experiment only requires simple observations to be made in the field": "",
  "Scientists use models or simulations when direct experimentation is impractical. For example, studying the formation of galaxies, predicting weather, or testing car crash safety requires simulations because real tests would be impossible, dangerous, or too expensive.": "",
  "Which investigation is best for studying how a volcanic eruption affects nearby ecosystems?": "",
  "A controlled experiment in a school laboratory": "",
  "An observational study of the ecosystem before and after the eruption": "",
  "A survey asking people what they think about volcanic eruptions": "",
  "A computer simulation that only uses hypothetical volcano data": "",
  "Since you cannot control a volcanic eruption, an observational study comparing the ecosystem before and after the event is the best approach. Scientists can document changes to wildlife, vegetation, and soil.": "",
  "A student tests whether salt concentration affects how fast ice melts. What type of investigation is this?": "",
  "A natural observation": "",
  "A computer simulation": "",
  "This is a controlled experiment because the student deliberately manipulates a variable (salt concentration) while controlling other factors, and measures the result (melting speed).": "",
  "A weather scientist uses computer programs to predict hurricane paths. What type of investigation is this?": "",
  "A controlled laboratory experiment": "",
  "A field observation of weather patterns": "",
  "A model or simulation based on data": "",
  "A survey of people affected by storms": "",
  "Using computer programs to predict hurricane paths is a simulation. The scientist inputs real data into mathematical models that simulate atmospheric conditions to forecast where the storm will go.": "",
  "What is a key limitation of observational studies compared to controlled experiments?": "",
  "They cannot establish cause-and-effect relationships between variables": "",
  "They always produce less accurate data than experiments in every case": "",
  "They are never used by professional scientists in any real research": "",
  "They require more money and equipment than controlled experiments do": "",
  "Observational studies can identify correlations (things that happen together) but cannot prove that one variable causes another because variables are not controlled. Only controlled experiments can establish causation.": "",
  "What is a controlled experiment?": "",
  "An investigation where one variable is changed while all others are kept constant": "",
  "An investigation where the scientist only observes without changing any variables": "",
  "An investigation that uses computer software to simulate a natural process": "",
  "An investigation where all variables are changed at the same time for testing": "",
  "A controlled experiment is an investigation where the scientist deliberately changes one variable (independent) while keeping all others constant, and measures the effect on another variable (dependent).": "",
  "What is an observational study?": "",
  "An investigation where data is collected by watching events without manipulating variables": "",
  "An investigation where the scientist changes one variable and measures the effect": "",
  "An investigation conducted only in a laboratory with specialized equipment on hand": "",
  "An investigation where the scientist creates a model to represent a real process": "",
  "An observational study involves watching, measuring, and recording data about events as they naturally occur without intervening or changing any variables. Field studies and surveys are common examples.": "",
  "What is a 'field study' in science?": "",
  "Research conducted in a natural environment rather than in a laboratory": "",
  "Research conducted only in agricultural fields on farms and ranches": "",
  "Research that involves studying only open grassy areas and meadows": "",
  "Research where the scientist controls every variable in a closed space": "",
  "A field study is research conducted in the natural environment where events occur, such as a forest, ocean, or desert. Scientists collect data in real-world conditions rather than in a controlled laboratory.": "",
  "What is a 'simulation' in scientific research?": "",
  "A computer-based or physical imitation of a real process used for studying it": "",
  "An experiment where all variables are kept exactly the same throughout testing": "",
  "A natural observation recorded without any interference by the scientist": "",
  "A measurement taken with an extremely precise instrument in a laboratory": "",
  "A simulation is a model that imitates a real-world process, often using computers. Simulations allow scientists to study systems that are too large, too fast, too slow, or too dangerous to study directly.": "",
  "What does 'descriptive investigation' mean?": "",
  "An investigation that describes and records observations without testing a hypothesis": "",
  "An investigation that uses only numbers and calculations with no word descriptions": "",
  "An investigation that tests multiple hypotheses at the same time in one experiment": "",
  "An investigation that provides a written description of the laboratory equipment": "",
  "A descriptive investigation involves observing and describing a subject or phenomenon without testing a specific hypothesis. Classifying rocks, cataloging species, or mapping terrain are examples.": "",
  "What does 'comparative investigation' mean?": "",
  "An investigation that compares two or more groups or conditions without manipulation": "",
  "An investigation where the scientist deliberately changes one variable being tested": "",
  "An investigation that uses only one group of subjects with no comparison made": "",
  "An investigation that compares the results from two completely different experiments": "",
  "A comparative investigation compares two or more groups, objects, or conditions to find similarities and differences. For example, comparing the soil in different locations or the behavior of different animal species.": "",
  "What does 'experimental investigation' mean?": "",
  "An investigation that uses manipulation of variables to test cause and effect": "",
  "Any scientific study regardless of whether variables are changed or controlled": "",
  "An investigation that only involves observing events in the natural environment": "",
  "An investigation that relies solely on predictions made before collecting data": "",
  "An experimental investigation involves deliberately manipulating one or more variables to observe the effect on an outcome. It is the most rigorous type of investigation for determining cause-and-effect relationships.": "",
  "What does 'correlation' mean in observational studies?": "",
  "A relationship where two variables change together but one may not cause the other": "",
  "A proven cause-and-effect link between two variables that has been confirmed": "",
  "A situation where two variables are completely unrelated to each other in all ways": "",
  "A mathematical error found during the analysis of experimental data in a lab": "",
  "Correlation means two variables change together in a pattern. However, correlation does not prove causation — the variables may both be influenced by a third factor rather than one causing the other.": "",
  "What does 'data collection' mean in an investigation?": "",
  "The process of gathering information through measurements, observations, or surveys": "",
  "The process of forming a hypothesis before any experiment has been performed": "",
  "The process of writing a conclusion after all experimental analysis is complete": "",
  "The process of selecting which equipment to use for a planned experiment": "",
  "Data collection is the systematic process of gathering information relevant to your investigation, whether through direct measurement, observation, surveys, or instrument readings.": "",
  "What is a 'survey' as a type of investigation?": "",
  "A method of gathering data by asking questions to a group of people": "",
  "A controlled experiment conducted in a laboratory setting with equipment": "",
  "A computer program that simulates natural processes using data inputs": "",
  "A measurement taken using a specific instrument such as a thermometer": "",
  "A survey is a data collection method that uses questionnaires or interviews to gather information from a group of people. Surveys are useful for studying opinions, behaviors, and trends in populations.": "",
  "A marine biologist wants to study how dolphins interact in their natural habitat. She spends months observing dolphins from a boat without disturbing them. What type of investigation is she conducting?": "",
  "A controlled experiment manipulating dolphin behavior": "",
  "A field observation study in the dolphins' natural habitat": "",
  "A computer simulation of dolphin swimming patterns": "",
  "A laboratory experiment testing dolphin intelligence levels": "",
  "This is a field observation study because the biologist is watching and recording dolphin behavior in their natural environment without manipulating any variables or interfering with their activities.": "",
  "An engineer wants to test whether a new bridge design can withstand strong winds. It would be too expensive and dangerous to build a full-size bridge just for testing. What type of investigation should she use?": "",
  "A field observation of existing bridges during storms": "",
  "A model or simulation to test the design before building": "",
  "A survey asking people if they think the bridge is safe": "",
  "A descriptive study documenting wind patterns in the area": "",
  "A model (physical scale model) or computer simulation allows the engineer to test the bridge design under various wind conditions without the cost and risk of building a full-size structure.": "",
  "A student wants to know if the brand of battery affects how long a flashlight shines. She buys three brands, puts each in the same flashlight, and times how long each lasts. What type of investigation is this?": "",
  "An observational study of battery performance in nature": "",
  "A controlled experiment comparing battery brands directly": "",
  "A simulation of battery life using computer software": "",
  "A descriptive study recording the appearance of batteries": "",
  "This is a controlled experiment because the student deliberately changes the independent variable (battery brand) while keeping other factors constant (same flashlight), and measures the dependent variable (time).": "",
  "A geologist studies rock layers in the Grand Canyon to understand Earth's history. She cannot manipulate the rock layers or change geological time. What type of investigation is most appropriate?": "",
  "A controlled experiment changing the conditions of rock formation": "",
  "An observational and descriptive study of existing rock formations": "",
  "A survey asking visitors what they think the rocks look like": "",
  "A laboratory experiment creating artificial rock layers from scratch": "",
  "Since the geologist cannot manipulate rock layers or geological processes, an observational/descriptive study is most appropriate. She observes, describes, and records the characteristics of existing formations.": "",
  "A climate scientist wants to predict how temperatures will change over the next 50 years. She cannot wait 50 years for real data. What type of investigation should she use?": "",
  "A controlled experiment in a laboratory over a 50-year period": "",
  "A computer simulation using current data to model future trends": "",
  "A field observation collecting temperature data for 50 more years": "",
  "A survey asking people what temperature they expect it to be": "",
  "A computer simulation can model future climate conditions based on current data and trends. Since waiting 50 years is impractical, simulations allow scientists to explore possible outcomes much faster.": "",
  "A student reads that people who exercise more tend to have lower blood pressure. She wants to prove exercise causes lower blood pressure. Can she conclude this from the study she read?": "",
  "Yes, because the study shows a clear cause-and-effect between the two factors": "",
  "No, because the study only shows correlation and would need a controlled experiment": "",
  "Yes, because all studies that show patterns automatically prove cause and effect": "",
  "No, because blood pressure cannot be affected by any lifestyle choices at all": "",
  "The study shows a correlation (exercise and lower blood pressure occur together) but not causation. Other factors could explain the relationship. A controlled experiment would be needed to establish cause and effect.": "",
  "An astronomer wants to study how stars form. She cannot create a star in a lab. What should she do?": "",
  "Give up because star formation cannot be studied without a controlled experiment": "",
  "Use observations of existing stars and computer simulations to study the process": "",
  "Conduct a survey asking other scientists what they think about star formation": "",
  "Only use data from textbooks and never conduct any new research on stars": "",
  "The astronomer can observe stars at different stages of formation using telescopes and use computer simulations to model the process. Many scientific phenomena are studied through combinations of observation and modeling.": "",
  "A student wants to compare the soil pH in three different parks. She collects soil samples and tests them but does not change any conditions. What type of investigation is she doing?": "",
  "A controlled experiment with an independent variable changed": "",
  "A comparative investigation looking at differences between sites": "",
  "A computer simulation modeling soil chemistry processes in parks": "",
  "An experimental investigation that will prove what causes pH levels": "",
  "This is a comparative investigation because she is comparing soil pH across three locations without manipulating any variables. She is looking for differences between the parks, not testing cause and effect.": "",
  "A teacher gives students a choice: study how temperature affects magnet strength (experiment) or study what types of rocks are found near school (observation). A student picks the observation study. What is one advantage of this choice?": "",
  "It can prove that certain conditions cause specific types of rocks to form": "",
  "It allows the student to study rocks in their real-world, natural environment": "",
  "It is the only type of investigation that produces reliable scientific data": "",
  "It requires no planning, preparation, or data recording from the student": "",
  "An observational study allows the student to examine rocks in their natural setting, which provides real-world context. However, she will not be able to determine cause-and-effect relationships from observations alone.": "",
  "NASA uses computer models to simulate how spacecraft will perform during launch. Why is a simulation better than a real test for the initial design phase?": "",
  "Simulations always give perfectly accurate results that match real launches exactly": "",
  "Simulations are cheaper and safer, allowing engineers to test many designs quickly": "",
  "Real rocket launches cannot be observed or measured by any scientific instruments": "",
  "Simulations require no data at all and are based entirely on random guesses only": "",
  "Computer simulations allow engineers to test hundreds of design variations quickly and safely without the enormous cost and risk of building and launching real rockets. Once a design passes simulation testing, real tests follow.": ""
}